The candidate clearly identifies the situation as train-serve (notebook-serve) skew and focuses on preprocessing drift rather than the model itself. They prescribe a strict parity test at the model input boundary with byte-level (torch.equal/allclose) comparison and enumerate common drift sources (tokenizer/vocab, normalization, resize, channel order, tabular encoders, padding/masks, dtype, eval mode). They also ask targeted questions about modality, shared preprocessing, and dependency versions. They explicitly say not to touch/retrain the model. All criteria are met.

